00:21:56.593 --> 00:21:59.858
I can get more enzyme into the cells.

235
00:22:01.297 --> 00:22:04.960
What's the matter, Sal?
Not up on your glycobiology?


236
00:22:05.902 --> 00:22:07.699
I thought Doc was just your nickname.

237
00:22:07.804 --> 00:22:11.001
No, that man's a genius. He's on the verge
of a scientific breakthrough.


238
00:22:11.107 --> 00:22:13.575
Wow. Who knew?

239
00:22:15.512 --> 00:22:19.380
I'm not on the verge of anything, kid.
This is a theory, not a therapy.


240
00:22:19.482 --> 00:22:21.473
I'm just an academic.

241
00:22:21.584 --> 00:22:24.917
- You got any idea how shitty my funding is?
- No.


242
00:22:25.989 --> 00:22:28.389
University of Nebraska
pays their football coach


243
00:22:28.491 --> 00:22:31.483
more money in a year
than my entire science budget.


244
00:22:31.594 --> 00:22:34.222
Nobody's paying attention to this work.

245
00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:36.525
Half my grants don't get approved.

246
00:22:36.633 --> 00:22:40.967
I don't have the money to make my theory
into a useable medicine.


247
00:22:42.105 --> 00:22:44.005
How old are your kids?

248
00:22:45.008 --> 00:22:46.600
Six and eight.

249
00:22:53.116 --> 00:22:57.519
Look, do yourself a favor.
Go home and spend time with your kids.


250
00:22:59.856 --> 00:23:02.620
Enjoy 'em while they're still here.

251
00:23:09.799 --> 00:23:11.926
- How much?
- How much what?


252
00:23:12.802 --> 00:23:15.862
How much money would it take
to prove your theory,


253
00:23:15.972 --> 00:23:19.430
to create your version of the medicine?

254
00:23:20.343 --> 00:23:23.710
I'd need half a million bucks
just to fund the lab work.


255
00:23:23.813 --> 00:23:26.805
- That's why you need me.
- I need you? Why?


256
00:23:26.916 --> 00:23:31.683
Because I'm the founder of
the Pompe Foundation for Children.


257
00:23:33.890 --> 00:23:36.552
I've been working on this disease
for 10 years.


258
00:23:36.659 --> 00:23:39.287
I have never heard of you guys.

259
00:23:39.395 --> 00:23:43.855
That's because we're relatively new.
We're just in the gearing-up phase.


260
00:23:44.767 --> 00:23:48.601
- How soon do you need a grant?
- Now would be good.


261
00:23:48.705 --> 00:23:53.039
Well, not all the money's in place,
but it will be, and soon.


262
00:23:55.845 --> 00:23:58.143
This is a very exciting time.

263
00:24:08.091 --> 00:24:10.992
- Thanks.
- Thank you, sir. Have a good day.


264
00:24:24.908 --> 00:24:26.102
Hey.

265
00:24:29.979 --> 00:24:31.378
You okay?

266
00:24:36.619 --> 00:24:39.611
- Did you get my messages?
- Your messages?


267
00:24:41.257 --> 00:24:43.157
You suddenly walk out of the meeting

268
00:24:43.259 --> 00:24:45.853
and fly to Nebraska
without talking to me about it,


269
00:24:45.962 --> 00:24:48.123
and you think messages make it okay?

270
00:24:48.231 --> 00:24:50.290
- I'm sorry.
- My God, John.


271
00:24:50.900 --> 00:24:53.391
I wanna find a miracle
as much as you do, okay?


272
00:24:53.503 --> 00:24:55.801
But how could you
put your job in jeopardy?

273
00:24:55.905 --> 00:24:57.372
- Aileen.
- How exactly


274
00:24:57.473 --> 00:25:00.840
do we pay $40,000 a month in healthcare
if you lose your insurance?


275
00:25:00.944 --> 00:25:02.411
Honey, come on.
Look, I'm not gonna lose my job.


276
00:25:02.512 --> 00:25:03.570
Oh, really?

277
00:25:03.680 --> 00:25:07.309
Pete called here twice last night
to ask if you were okay.


278
00:25:07.417 --> 00:25:09.214
You know, mentally.

279
00:25:16.526 --> 00:25:20.121
I'll just...
I'll call, and I'll smooth that one over.


280
00:25:20.463 --> 00:25:21.987
Yeah, no shit.

281
00:25:27.003 --> 00:25:28.436
I'm sorry.

282
00:25:32.809 --> 00:25:35.607
Something in me just kind of snapped.

283
00:25:36.646 --> 00:25:40.980
That night at the hospital,
when we thought that we were losing her,


284
00:25:46.689 --> 00:25:50.489
I prayed that if it was her time,

285
00:25:52.795 --> 00:25:57.459
she'd go quickly, without so much suffering.

286
00:26:01.137 --> 00:26:05.437
But morning came, and she pulled through.

287
00:26:07.677 --> 00:26:09.167
Her eyes,

288
00:26:10.980 --> 00:26:14.006
so determined, so defiant.

289
00:26:15.251 --> 00:26:17.014
The fight in her.

290
00:26:28.164 --> 00:26:30.962
Was he worth it? 
This Stonehill guy?

291
00:26:31.067 --> 00:26:34.730
He's really eccentric, but his science
is way ahead of everybody else's.


292
00:26:34.837 --> 00:26:38.967
- He's definitely the one to put our money on.
- Lf we had any.


293
00:26:39.075 --> 00:26:41.305
I promised him that we'd raise some,

294
00:26:41.411 --> 00:26:43.606
because he's got this conference up here
next month,


295
00:26:43.713 --> 00:26:46.079
and I said I'd have
a check ready for him.

296
00:26:46.182 --> 00:26:47.342
- How much?
- Five hundred.


297
00:26:47.450 --> 00:26:49.509
- That's all?
- Thousand.


298
00:26:51.254 --> 00:26:53.313
Is it $500 or $1,000?

299
00:26:53.589 --> 00:26:55.853
$500,000.

300
00:26:56.926 --> 00:26:58.484
By next month.

301
00:27:04.133 --> 00:27:08.399
- Sweetheart, are you totally insane?
- Apparently.


302
00:27:09.305 --> 00:27:12.035
We're holding our first fundraiser
on the 23rd at the school,


303
00:27:12.141 --> 00:27:14.507
and we would love
if you and Frank could join us.


304
00:27:14.610 --> 00:27:16.305
- Ready for your spelling test?
- I'm gonna nail it.


305
00:27:16.412 --> 00:27:17.470
Okay. Good luck.

306
00:27:17.580 --> 00:27:19.775
My name's John Crowley.
I'm calling from Oregon,


307
00:27:19.882 --> 00:27:24.342
and I got your name from
the Atlanta-area Pompe parents<i>'</i> group.


308
00:27:24.454 --> 00:27:25.478
Yeah.

309
00:27:25.588 --> 00:27:27.783
And I was so sorry
not to see you at the reunion


310
00:27:27.890 --> 00:27:32.020
because you were one of
my most favorite people in high school.


311
00:27:32.895 --> 00:27:36.387
Anyway, John and I
are starting this foundation.


312
00:27:36.499 --> 00:27:38.228
- Hey, Dad? Dad.
- No, you know what I mean.


313
00:27:38.334 --> 00:27:39.392
Just make it right.

314
00:27:39.502 --> 00:27:42.494
- Dad?
- Can't you see I'm on the phone?


315
00:27:42.605 --> 00:27:44.869
- Okay, well, tell me what he told you.
- Dad!


316
00:27:44.974 --> 00:27:47.534
No, I'm gonna have to call you back.
I can't talk. All right, bye.


317
00:27:47.643 --> 00:27:49.543
- Yeah, what is it?
- I sold my RipStik.


318
00:27:49.645 --> 00:27:50.634
Okay.

319
00:27:51.147 --> 00:27:54.810
Is it enough to give to
Megan and Patrick's foundation?


320
00:27:57.487 --> 00:27:59.751
Yeah, it's more than enough.

321
00:28:02.024 --> 00:28:03.924
- Are you John?
- Yes.


322
00:28:04.026 --> 00:28:07.484
- Marcus Temple. We spoke on the phone.
- Right. Absolutely. Good to see you.


323
00:28:07.597 --> 00:28:10.191
- All the way in from Atlanta.
- Yes.


324
00:28:10.299 --> 00:28:15.396
Well, this is for your foundation,
from my relatives, friends and church group.


325
00:28:16.639 --> 00:28:18.106
My goodness.

326
00:28:18.541 --> 00:28:20.338
Thank you very much.

327
00:28:25.515 --> 00:28:26.812
Thanks.

328
00:28:46.135 --> 00:28:51.232
- Hi, Dr. Stonehill. I'm Megan.
- Hi, Megan. I'm Dr. Stonehill.


329
00:28:51.340 --> 00:28:54.434
Yeah, that's why I said, "Hi, Dr. Stonehill."

330
00:28:55.178 --> 00:28:58.705
- Are you coming in or not?
