the rate of cardiac enlargement.


816
01:06:26.493 --> 01:06:29.587
- We'll keep tabs on their other organs...
- How long?


817
01:06:31.231 --> 01:06:33.927
- I don't like to predict.
- Please.


818
01:06:34.034 --> 01:06:36.935
Dr. Waldman, we won't hold you to it.
We just need to know something.


819
01:06:37.037 --> 01:06:38.595
John.

820
01:06:38.906 --> 01:06:42.672
How much more time do we have?
How long?


821
01:06:44.278 --> 01:06:45.677
Well,

822
01:06:48.949 --> 01:06:52.680
if there's another respiratory crisis,
all bets are off,


823
01:06:53.353 --> 01:06:56.151
but otherwise,

824
01:06:58.859 --> 01:07:01.054
Megan, maybe a year.

825
01:07:01.695 --> 01:07:04.061
Patrick, less.

826
01:07:07.701 --> 01:07:09.100
Thank you.

827
01:07:23.984 --> 01:07:25.212
Marcus.

828
01:07:25.319 --> 01:07:26.377
- Get the phone.
- What?


829
01:07:26.487 --> 01:07:28.455
- The phone.
- Who is it?


830
01:07:29.256 --> 01:07:32.089
<i>- Hello?</i>
- Hi. Is that Marcus?


831
01:07:32.226 --> 01:07:35.218
<i>- Yeah, yeah. What time is it?</i>
- Yeah, I'm sorry. It's late.


832
01:07:35.896 --> 01:07:39.093
<i>- It's John Crowley.</i>
- John, what you doin'


833
01:07:40.434 --> 01:07:41.526
You okay?

834
01:07:43.670 --> 01:07:47.436
Hey, look, I gotta ask you a favor.

835
01:07:48.308 --> 01:07:49.900
- Morning, Gavin.
- Morning, sir.


836
01:07:50.010 --> 01:07:51.602
Is my 11:00 with Henessey confirmed?

837
01:07:51.712 --> 01:07:55.546
Yes, and there's the breakfast meeting
down in the cafeteria.


838
01:07:55.649 --> 01:07:57.048
Breakfast meeting?

839
01:07:57.151 --> 01:07:59.711
There was an e-mail that came in
over the weekend.


840
01:07:59.820 --> 01:08:01.617
Everyone on the Pompe project was invited.

841
01:08:01.755 --> 01:08:04.690
- Who called the meeting?
- Mr. Crowley, I believe, sir.


842
01:08:04.792 --> 01:08:06.089
What?

843
01:08:09.963 --> 01:08:15.128
Something that people ask me all the time
is how we have two kids with Pompe.


844
01:08:15.969 --> 01:08:20.065
By the time we realized
that Megan had Pompe,


845
01:08:21.074 --> 01:08:23.167
I was already pregnant with Patrick.

846
01:08:23.277 --> 01:08:26.075
I mean, I can't tell you
how many doctors we saw,


847
01:08:26.180 --> 01:08:27.909
and the message was always the same,

848
01:08:28.015 --> 01:08:31.212
that there is no drug to treat Pompe.

849
01:08:31.318 --> 01:08:35.152
But thanks to you, all of you,
that message is changing.


850
01:08:35.255 --> 01:08:39.715
What you've given us,
and a lot of other families, is hope.


851
01:08:39.827 --> 01:08:41.385
So, thank you.

852
01:08:42.663 --> 01:08:44.494
Good job, Aileen.

853
01:08:47.301 --> 01:08:50.361
Now I'd like to welcome the Temple family,

854
01:08:50.470 --> 01:08:54.497
who've come all the way from Georgia
to be with us here today.


855
01:09:00.314 --> 01:09:01.941
Thanks, John.

856
01:09:05.118 --> 01:09:06.312
Hi.

857
01:09:07.888 --> 01:09:09.480
I'm Marcus.

858
01:09:10.624 --> 01:09:12.785
This is my wife, Wendy.

859
01:09:12.893 --> 01:09:15.794
Our daughter Lauren, our oldest daughter,

860
01:09:15.896 --> 01:09:20.856
Lauren wanted to come today
and say hi to all you guys.


861
01:09:22.903 --> 01:09:24.393
She's a little weak,

862
01:09:24.504 --> 01:09:29.635
but she wanted us
to show you guys her picture


863
01:09:30.143 --> 01:09:32.771
and to send you her love.

864
01:09:33.680 --> 01:09:36.911
And this is our daughter, Megan.

865
01:09:37.017 --> 01:09:40.453
The most beautiful girls are named Megan.

866
01:09:41.555 --> 01:09:45.685
Megan is four months old,
and you can't see it yet,


867
01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:49.051
but she has Pompe, too.

868
01:10:03.010 --> 01:10:04.375
I...

869
01:10:06.413 --> 01:10:10.349
I can't tell you
what it means to us

870
01:10:12.052 --> 01:10:16.421
to have all of you working on a medicine
for our children.


871
01:10:19.192 --> 01:10:20.591
Thank you.

872
01:10:27.401 --> 01:10:29.028
Thanks so much.

873
01:10:37.477 --> 01:10:39.604
- Hey, Kent.
- John.


874
01:10:39.713 --> 01:10:42.341
So what did you think of the event?

875
01:10:47.821 --> 01:10:53.225
In medical research, John,
objectivity is key.


876
01:10:54.728 --> 01:10:57.822
If researchers get all emotional,

877
01:10:57.931 --> 01:11:02.527
all desperate to help suffering patients,
they'll cut corners.


878
01:11:02.636 --> 01:11:03.830
It's counterproductive.

879
01:11:03.937 --> 01:11:08.670
Counterproductive is having
four core teams of scientists


880
01:11:08.775 --> 01:11:13.212
working together on the same disease,
but not talking to each other.


881
01:11:13.747 --> 01:11:17.080
Most of these guys have never
even seen a kid with Pompe before.


882
01:11:17.184 --> 01:11:18.947
I don't see how that's relevant.

883
01:11:19.086 --> 01:11:23.318
Did you see Erich?
That's the kind of motivation that we need.


884
01:11:23.423 --> 01:11:27.860
I'm gonna ask him to get the core team
