01:15:34.541 --> 01:15:35.803
She...

944
01:15:39.212 --> 01:15:41.942
He said she went in her sleep,
that it was peaceful.


945
01:15:42.048 --> 01:15:43.640
How old is she?

946
01:15:45.018 --> 01:15:46.918
How old was Lauren?

947
01:15:52.192 --> 01:15:54.353
Lauren was nine years old.

948
01:16:01.968 --> 01:16:03.492
Come here.

949
01:16:13.780 --> 01:16:17.614
That way, we can be certain
that we're developing the correct one.


950
01:16:17.884 --> 01:16:24.016
Forget certainty, and let's try and figure out
which enzyme has the better odds.


951
01:16:24.224 --> 01:16:26.852
If we develop only one enzyme,

952
01:16:28.328 --> 01:16:30.125
what would happen
if we guessed the wrong one?


953
01:16:30.230 --> 01:16:35.224
Mr. Crowley, I've asked Kent
to set up a testing protocol


954
01:16:35.335 --> 01:16:37.530
to help us guess right.

955
01:16:38.271 --> 01:16:41.138
We'll do an exhaustive range of tests.

956
01:16:41.241 --> 01:16:44.972
I'm calling it
"The Mother of All Experiments."


957
01:16:46.946 --> 01:16:51.440
The four enzymes will be color-coded,
yellow, blue, green and magenta,


958
01:16:51.584 --> 01:16:53.643
and known only by those color codes

959
01:16:53.787 --> 01:16:56.984
so no researcher will know
which one he's testing.


960
01:16:57.123 --> 01:17:01.423
Only after we pick a winner,
the secret identity will be revealed.


961
01:17:08.268 --> 01:17:09.929
Come on, Megan!

962
01:17:21.648 --> 01:17:22.740
But I want to!

963
01:17:28.288 --> 01:17:30.848
- Just roll your wrist.
- I can't.


964
01:17:35.328 --> 01:17:36.989
It's okay. It's all right. 
Let's try another one.

965
01:17:37.130 --> 01:17:39.621
Okay. Let's try again. Ready?

966
01:17:41.868 --> 01:17:43.267
Ready?

967
01:17:43.370 --> 01:17:45.531
One, two, three, go!

968
01:17:47.874 --> 01:17:50.274
- Big winner!
- Yay!


969
01:17:51.478 --> 01:17:54.811
Here you go, look at that. 
You got a penguin.

970
01:18:04.524 --> 01:18:06.492
Hey, Bob. Bob.

971
01:18:08.595 --> 01:18:10.187
How you doin'

972
01:18:15.835 --> 01:18:17.894
I brought you some ribs.

973
01:18:18.705 --> 01:18:22.072
Not as good as the ones
from The Corner Saloon,


974
01:18:22.175 --> 01:18:24.200
but if you're hungry...

975
01:18:34.854 --> 01:18:36.549
What do you want?

976
01:18:39.526 --> 01:18:41.153
The results.

977
01:18:42.729 --> 01:18:44.594
"Mother of All Experiments."

978
01:18:44.731 --> 01:18:45.993
Well,

979
01:18:48.234 --> 01:18:50.327
which enzyme did they choose?

980
01:18:50.437 --> 01:18:53.998
The leadership team
spent the whole afternoon arguing.


981
01:18:54.107 --> 01:18:57.543
Two enzymes, coded yellow and green,
are ahead of the others,


982
01:18:57.644 --> 01:18:59.942
but it's too close to call.

983
01:19:00.079 --> 01:19:05.176
Tomorrow, we spend the day hashing it out
to decide which one to choose.


984
01:19:06.986 --> 01:19:10.615
Bob. I'm asking you to read this.

985
01:19:11.257 --> 01:19:14.693
I value your opinion
more than anyone else in the world.


986
01:19:14.794 --> 01:19:17.354
Well, maybe you should have valued
my opinion a little sooner,


987
01:19:17.464 --> 01:19:21.025
instead of playing hatchet man
for the bean counters.


988
01:19:22.135 --> 01:19:26.697
- Get the hell out of my lab.
- It's in your interest to know about this, Bob.


989
01:19:29.809 --> 01:19:31.208
Get out.

990
01:19:31.311 --> 01:19:33.939
- Wouldn't it benefit you...
- Get out.


991
01:19:58.371 --> 01:20:03.001
The green enzyme's the best.
Show 'em my analysis, they'll understand.


992
01:20:04.110 --> 01:20:05.805
Hey, wait up, Bob.

993
01:20:06.813 --> 01:20:08.678
Is the green enzyme yours?

994
01:20:08.815 --> 01:20:12.751
I recognize patterns in the results.
I'd know my baby a mile away.


995
01:20:12.852 --> 01:20:15.320
- So the green one is yours?
- No.


996
01:20:15.855 --> 01:20:17.447
No, it's not.

997
01:20:20.193 --> 01:20:24.357
My theory is still the best,
but it's not ready for manufacture.


998
01:20:25.632 --> 01:20:28.795
Theirs is crude and uninspired,
but it's ready.


999
01:20:30.470 --> 01:20:33.871
Bob, I don't even know the words
to say thank you.


1000
01:20:34.874 --> 01:20:36.341
Don't bother.

1001
01:20:38.511 --> 01:20:40.536
I didn't do it for you.

1002
01:21:27.393 --> 01:21:28.758
Yes, it is!

1003
01:21:31.564 --> 01:21:33.532
- Oh, my gosh. Do you see the kite up there?
- Yeah.


1004
01:21:33.633 --> 01:21:34.759
That's so cool!

1005
01:21:34.901 --> 01:21:36.562
Annie, careful!

1006
01:21:37.203 --> 01:21:39.171
- Building a bastion.
- Right there. Yeah.


1007
01:21:44.310 --> 01:21:45.436
- Three!
- Okay!


1008
01:21:45.545 --> 01:21:46.637
Dad, like... Ready?

1009
01:21:46.746 --> 01:21:50.182
- Dad, you promised no more phone calls.
- I know. I know I did, but...


1010
01:21:50.283 --> 01:21:51.307
What's in there?

1011
01:21:51.417 --> 01:21:53.715
We can take turns burying the phone
when I get back.


1012
01:21:53.820 --> 01:21:55.378
Okay! I'll start digging a hole.

1013
01:21:55.488 --> 01:21:58.116
- You hold that for a sec.
- John Crowley.


1014
01:21:58.625 --> 01:22:00.422
John, it's Kent Weber.

1015
01:22:00.560 --> 01:22:03.723
Kent, hey. Did you get
my suggested protocol for the clinical trials?


1016
01:22:05.064 --> 01:22:06.258
Yeah.

1017
01:22:07.800 --> 01:22:09.859
You made some
pretty optimistic assumptions


1018
01:22:09.969 --> 01:22:12.767
about where our enzyme supply will be.

1019
01:22:13.306 --> 01:22:14.603
I see.

1020
01:22:15.475 --> 01:22:20.003
Well, what do you think
that a more realistic...


1021
01:22:20.113 --> 01:22:25.881
John, I'll give it to you straight.
The clinical trial will be for infants only.


1022
01:22:27.186 --> 01:22:29.586
<i>Infants need so much less enzyme,</i>

1023
01:22:29.689 --> 01:22:32.487
<i>and, as you know,</i>
<i>our initial supply will be so limited.</i>


1024
01:22:32.959 --> 01:22:36.690
And the drug has much higher odds
of being effective


1025
01:22:36.796 --> 01:22:39.356
with infants than with older children.

1026
01:22:39.465 --> 01:22:42.901
We have to consult Erich on this.
We have to consult Erich.


1027
01:22:43.469 --> 01:22:46.336
I already did. He confirmed the decision.
Infants only.


1028
01:22:46.839 --> 01:22:49.933
<i>I understand your personal reasons for...</i>

1029
01:22:52.712 --> 01:22:57.945
These decisions have to be
made objectively, rationally.


1030
01:22:59.152 --> 01:23:01.279
I'm sorry. I...

1031
01:23:02.955 --> 01:23:03.979
I really am.

1032
01:26:17.650 --> 01:26:19.174
Hold it, pal.

1033
01:26:22.688 --> 01:26:26.180
- Mr. Crowley, what are you doin<i>'</i> in here?
- I was just...


1034
01:26:26.292 --> 01:26:29.921
- You're not authorized.
- No... I can explain everything.


1035
01:26:30.029 --> 01:26:31.894
What's the matter, Chuck?
Is there a problem?


1036
01:26:31.998 --> 01:26:35.456
Yeah, there's a problem.
I got Mr. Crowley in here without clearance.


1037
01:26:35.568 --> 01:26:36.933
That's my fault, now.

1038
01:26:37.036 --> 01:26:42.269
I got busy in the lab, I sent Jersey boy here
to get me a couple jugs of enzyme.


1039
01:26:42.842 --> 01:26:44.139
Sorry.

1040
01:26:54.220 --> 01:26:55.778
Thanks, Chuck.

1041
01:27:02.194 --> 01:27:04.355
Thanks for saving my ass.

1042
01:27:05.765 --> 01:27:07.790
It's really big of you,

1043
01:27:07.900 --> 01:27:12.496
especially after what went down between us.

1044
01:27:13.940 --> 01:27:17.239
You mean your ruthless,
cold-hearted betrayal?


1045
01:27:20.513 --> 01:27:24.540
Yeah, well, when I thought about it
from your point of view...


1046
01:27:25.284 --> 01:27:30.381
Shit, if it was my kids dying, I wouldn't
have hesitated to crush you like a bug.


1047
01:27:44.971 --> 01:27:47.235
Do you remember when we first met,

1048
01:27:47.373 --> 01:27:52.538
and you told me that
I should stop chasing miracles


1049
01:27:52.645 --> 01:27:55.546
and should go home and enjoy my kids,

1050
01:27:56.916 --> 01:27:59.077
while they're still here?

1051
01:28:03.923 --> 01:28:06.414
- Yeah.
- I made the wrong choice.


1052
01:28:22.375 --> 01:28:26.334
- Jersey, you know what a sibling study is?
- No.


1053
01:28:26.445 --> 01:28:31.314
It's a drug trial with just two patients
with the same genetic inheritance.


1054
01:28:32.551 --> 01:28:36.317
Siblings, with the same disease.

1055
01:28:36.422 --> 01:28:38.151
Megs and Patrick.

1056
01:28:40.159 --> 01:28:43.424
Well, would Zymagen
go for something like this?


1057
01:28:44.497 --> 01:28:47.295
There's real research value in it.

1058
01:28:47.466 --> 01:28:50.731
And with just two patients,
it wouldn't take much enzyme.


1059
01:28:50.836 --> 01:28:53.805
But Webber would have
to sign off on it.

1060
01:28:54.974 --> 01:28:58.466
Well, let's not tell him
till we've got our ducks in a row.


1061
01:28:58.611 --> 01:29:03.913
I could draw up a protocol and see if I can
find a hospital willing to administer it.


1062
01:29:04.784 --> 01:29:08.584
- Bob.
- Well, don't get your hopes up, kid.


1063
01:29:10.890 --> 01:29:12.653
It's a Hail Mary.

1064
01:29:44.924 --> 01:29:46.551
Ducks in a row.

1065
01:29:49.528 --> 01:29:51.894
"Stonehill, careful review, protocol,
Sibling Trial,146,


1066
01:29:51.997 --> 01:29:53.430
"are pleased to inform you Megan Crowley
and Patrick


1067
01:29:53.532 --> 01:29:55.056
"have been accepted into the trial!"

1068
01:29:55.234 --> 01:29:57.930
- I just got it.
- Quack, quack, quack.


1069
01:29:58.037 --> 01:29:59.334
Have you talked to him yet?

1070
01:29:59.438 --> 01:30:03.670
No. I did the science. 
You make the sale.

1071
01:30:05.578 --> 01:30:06.977
Thank you.

1072
01:30:07.446 --> 01:30:09.311
- Good luck.
- Right.


1073
01:30:16.088 --> 01:30:17.988
- Does he have about five?
- He does, yeah.


1074
01:30:18.090 --> 01:30:20.558
- Thanks.
- No problem, Mr. Crowley.


1075
01:30:22.461 --> 01:30:24.429
Hey, Kent? Knock-knock.

1076
01:30:26.632 --> 01:30:28.099
Got a minute?

1077
01:30:29.735 --> 01:30:30.997
Kent?

1078
01:30:32.304 --> 01:30:36.502
- Do you have any idea what you've done?
- Excuse me?


1079
01:30:36.609 --> 01:30:39.100
We got a call this morning
from Portland Rose Hospital,


1080
01:30:39.211 --> 01:30:41.372
about sending them enzyme for your kids?

1081
01:30:41.480 --> 01:30:44.005
Right. Yeah, I know.
That's what I'm here to talk to you about.


1082
01:30:44.116 --> 01:30:47.984
You and Stonehill set this up behind
my back. Now you come to me.


1083
01:30:48.087 --> 01:30:49.987
It's all tentative.

1084
01:30:50.089 --> 01:30:54.185
You want this company
to sponsor a drug study,


1085
01:30:54.293 --> 01:30:58.627
for two children whose father
is an executive of this company?


1086
01:30:58.731 --> 01:31:00.722
Have you never heard the term
"conflict of interest?"


1087
01:31:00.833 --> 01:31:01.993
It has nothing to do with a...

1088
01:31:02.101 --> 01:31:03.898
Do you know what the FDA would do
if they found out?


1089
01:31:04.003 --> 01:31:07.200
There is strong scientific justification
for this study.


1090
01:31:07.306 --> 01:31:09.171
There is great research value.

1091
01:31:09.275 --> 01:31:12.403
I'm a doctor, John.
I know the research value!


1092
01:31:13.279 --> 01:31:16.510
But you guys just can't go off half-cocked
without consulting us!


1093
01:31:16.615 --> 01:31:18.583
And I'm sure that if we just go
and talk to Erich, we can...


1094
01:31:18.684 --> 01:31:20.083
Erich already knows.

1095
01:31:20.186 --> 01:31:24.020
- He's furious about being blindsided.
- I didn't try to blindside anyone.


1096
01:31:24.123 --> 01:31:27.718
This is the reason
why we have a reporting structure,


1097
01:31:27.826 --> 01:31:31.660
why we have established procedure,
why there is protocol.


1098
01:31:33.465 --> 01:31:36.025
You heartless, bloodless machine.

1099
01:31:36.135 --> 01:31:39.696
You just have to fight me
every step of the way! Don't you?


1100
01:31:39.805 --> 01:31:43.673
You just hated it when I brought
the kids with Pompe to the doorstep!


1101
01:31:43.776 --> 01:31:47.678
You weren't thinking about those kids when
you put your children into that program


1102
01:31:47.780 --> 01:31:52.683
and jeopardized a decade's worth of
research investment made by this company!


1103
01:31:52.785 --> 01:31:55.413
This is not about
a return on an investment!

1104
01:31:55.521 --> 01:31:57.250
It's about kids,

1105
01:31:58.157 --> 01:32:00.853
kids with names, dreams,

1106
01:32:02.528 --> 01:32:04.655
families that love them.

1107
01:32:05.297 --> 01:32:09.529
You've jeopardized your chances
of ever getting your kids treated.


1108
01:32:38.030 --> 01:32:41.295
I'm not arguing science with you!

1109
01:32:42.268 --> 01:32:44.862
On every level!
On every level, you've stood...


1110
01:33:00.686 --> 01:33:03.985
I was just drafting a letter of apology
for senior management,


1111
01:33:04.089 --> 01:33:07.024
but I guess we're past that point.

1112
01:33:08.794 --> 01:33:12.890
I just spoke to Erich,
and we are terminating your employment.


1113
01:33:14.566 --> 01:33:16.500
Okay, I'll pack up my stuff.

1114
01:33:16.602 --> 01:33:18.627
Just one thing, John.

1115
01:33:18.737 --> 01:33:23.606
I may well be
a tight-ass pencil-pushing company man,


1116
01:33:23.709 --> 01:33:26.007
but I resent being called heartless.

1117
01:33:26.111 --> 01:33:28.511
- Look...
- Just let me finish.


1118
01:33:29.481 --> 01:33:31.813
The reason we're terminating
your employment,


1119
01:33:31.917 --> 01:33:34.886
is to eliminate the conflict of interest.

1120
01:33:35.587 --> 01:33:39.990
This strategy was brought to my attention
by our colleague, Dr. Stonehill,


1121
01:33:40.092 --> 01:33:42.185
in rather crude terms.

1122
01:33:43.829 --> 01:33:46.957
This will allow the sibling trial to proceed

1123
01:33:47.766 --> 01:33:50.360
for its purely scientific value.

1124
01:33:54.673 --> 01:33:57.938
Have your desk cleared out
by the end of the day.


1125
01:33:58.911 --> 01:34:01.072
Kent, what's with the...

1126
01:34:04.149 --> 01:34:08.711
I wanted to make sure you didn't
punch me out before I could tell you.


1127
01:34:09.988 --> 01:34:11.250
Well,

1128
01:34:13.759 --> 01:34:17.092
- thank you very much for firing me.
- My pleasure.


1129
01:34:17.629 --> 01:34:19.927
- I never liked you.
- Likewise.


1130
01:34:24.470 --> 01:34:25.767
Hey, you guys,
bring anything you want extra...


1131
01:34:25.871 --> 01:34:26.895
- Mom! Mom!
- What?


1132
01:34:27.005 --> 01:34:28.768
- Can I bring the bow and arrow?
- Yes, yes.


1133
01:34:32.511 --> 01:34:33.773
Hey!

1134
01:34:39.551 --> 01:34:41.143
John, what...

1135
01:34:42.121 --> 01:34:43.281
What?

1136
01:34:44.289 --> 01:34:49.693
We have a usable enzyme
that's ready for clinical trials.


1137
01:34:52.631 --> 01:34:54.531
When? When will it be ready?

1138
01:34:54.633 --> 01:34:58.433
Megs and Patrick start their infusions
before the end of this month.


1139
01:34:58.537 --> 01:35:00.664
- Oh, my God.
- Yeah.


1140
01:35:02.007 --> 01:35:03.474
Oh, my God.

1141
01:35:05.677 --> 01:35:06.871
John.

1142
01:35:07.546 --> 01:35:09.571
Hey, John, Daddy's here.

1143
01:35:09.681 --> 01:35:11.808
- Oh, hi, guys.
- Hey, Dad.


1144
01:35:12.684 --> 01:35:14.447
Why is Mommy sad?

1145
01:35:15.521 --> 01:35:18.319
Not sad, baby, so happy.

1146
01:35:21.660 --> 01:35:22.991
So happy.

1147
01:35:23.095 --> 01:35:24.995
Why is Mommy being so weird?

1148
01:35:25.097 --> 01:35:27.759
Well, it's because
we got the special medicine


1149
01:35:27.866 --> 01:35:31.302
for you, Megs, and for you, Patrick,
and you're gonna get it really soon.


1150
01:35:31.403 --> 01:35:32.836
That's great!

1151
01:35:48.420 --> 01:35:50.888
So, who wants to push the button?

1152
01:36:04.470 --> 01:36:07.234
Megs, Patrick, you ready?

1153
01:36:26.425 --> 01:36:28.689
When will we know if it's working?

1154
01:36:28.794 --> 01:36:30.853
It'll be a while, honey.

1155
01:36:30.963 --> 01:36:32.555
It's not pink.

1156
01:37:12.137 --> 01:37:15.470
Excuse me?
Your Uncle Bobby is here.


1157
01:37:17.142 --> 01:37:18.632
I don't know.

1158
01:37:25.717 --> 01:37:28.345
- You can go back if you like.
- Okay.


1159
01:37:33.792 --> 01:37:35.851
- John.
- Uncle Bobby.


1160
01:37:37.029 --> 01:37:40.157
They wouldn't let me
in unless I was family.

1161
01:37:42.901 --> 01:37:45.961
- Some things for the kids.
- Thanks.


1162
01:37:46.071 --> 01:37:47.663
Sleeping, huh?

1163
01:37:53.045 --> 01:37:55.036
Hey, thanks for coming.

1164
01:37:59.017 --> 01:38:02.111
I'm a scientist. 
Gotta track the experiment.

1165
01:38:11.563 --> 01:38:15.021
I wish your enzyme was the one
that passed the test.


1166
01:38:15.500 --> 01:38:20.995
But the one the kids are getting,
it's the right one, right? I mean...


1167
01:38:21.740 --> 01:38:23.640
It's gonna help them.

1168
01:38:28.113 --> 01:38:30.638
Yeah, you guys have done
everything humanly possible.


1169
01:38:30.749 --> 01:38:34.981
We just have to
see what the tests show.

1170
01:38:37.723 --> 01:38:40.624
You and I have had our differences,

1171
01:38:40.726 --> 01:38:44.218
and I just want you to know something.

1172
01:38:45.263 --> 01:38:46.821
I want you to know that...

1173
01:38:46.932 --> 01:38:48.729
- Yeah.
- Don't interrupt.


1174
01:38:48.834 --> 01:38:50.062
Okay.

1175
01:38:51.737 --> 01:38:55.764
I want you to know
that I appreciate everything


1176
01:38:55.874 --> 01:38:57.774
that you've done for Megs and Patrick,

1177
01:38:57.876 --> 01:39:01.471
and I'm never gonna forget it
for the rest of my life.


1178
01:39:05.183 --> 01:39:07.151
Not gonna kiss me, is he?

1179
01:39:07.252 --> 01:39:09.152
